Aha. I'm going to be annoying and ask to restructure this test. Consider num_trailing_dims=2. Let `values.shape = (6, 7, 8, 9, 2, 3)`, just for the sake of an example. The first four  entries are interpolation axes, and there are 2*3=6 trailing values to broadcast over. I think the test should actually loop over these six values, not only three values it does now. 

The shape of the result is checked above (line 533), so here we only check the values themselves. Options: 1) restrict to the test to two trailing dimensions, type the double loop manually; 2) reshape values to squash the trailing dimensions into one, keep the single for loop, restore the shape of the result before `assert_allclose` in line 548 below --- whichever feels more natural to you.
